,"severity":"Medium","confidence":"low","title":"zapOut uses the requested withdrawal amount instead of the amount actually delivered by the batcher","locations":["onchain_auto/0xd248b30a3207a766d318c7a87f5cf334a439446d/src/Zapper.sol:74","onchain_auto/0xd248b30a3207a766d318c7a87f5cf334a439446d/src/Zapper.sol:133","onchain_auto/0xd248b30a3207a766d318c7a87f5cf334a439446d/src/Zapper.sol:138"],"claim":"After `completeWithdrawalWithZap(zapCall.amountIn, msg.sender)`, the zapper never measures how many want tokens it actually received. It only checks whether its current want-token balance is at least the caller-supplied nominal `zapCall.amountIn`, then approves and swaps that full nominal amount.","impact":"If the batcher ever under-delivers, rounds down, or partially fulfills while the zapper already holds residual want tokens, the caller can consume that residue as if it were part of their own withdrawal. This can misattribute previously stranded funds to the next zap-out caller.","paths":["The zapper already holds some residual want tokens from earlier overpayments, accidental transfers, or failed token movements","A caller invokes `zapOut` with `amountIn` greater than the batcher actually transfers in this transaction","Because the contract checks only total current balance, `zap()` can approve and swap the residual balance together with the fresh withdrawal, effectively subsidizing the caller with pre-existing funds"],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1","opencode_1","merge_reviewer"]}],"rejected_candidates":[{"title":"Missing slippage protection for batcher withdrawal in zapOut","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Final-output slippage is already user-bounded by `minAmountOut`; the reportable edge case is the separate stale-balance subsidy issue captured in F-005, not a generic lack of slippage protection."},{"title":"No zero-address validation for governance in sweep","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"This only turns a governance misconfiguration into governance self-harm; it is not a permissionless or protocol-level exploit in the zapper itself."},{"title":"Missing event emissions for governance operations","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Observability issue only; no realistic fund-loss, theft, lockup, or DoS impact."},{"title":"Unchecked call return values in zap function","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"The low-level call success flag is checked, and swap success is further bounded by balance-delta plus `minAmountOut`; the meaningful risk from a no-op target is the persistent arbitrary approval issue already captured in F-001/F-003."},{"title":"Floating pragma allows incompatible compiler versions","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Informational build-hygiene concern, not a concrete protocol-level vulnerability."},{"title":"No access control on critical functions","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"`sweep()` is explicitly restricted to `vault.governance()`; a compromised governance key is an out-of-scope trust assumption, not a missing access control bug."}]}
